"use strict";(self.webpackChunk_N_E=self.webpackChunk_N_E||[]).push([[5366],{95366:function(e){e.exports=JSON.parse('[{"id":"q1","category":"Theory","question":"PostgreSQL writes changes to a sequential Write-Ahead Log (WAL) before applying them to data pages. Why is this architecture used instead of writing directly to data pages on every transaction?","options":["WAL compresses data to reduce storage consumption by up to 80%","Sequential WAL appends are 10–100x faster than random I/O writes to data pages, and WAL enables crash recovery (replay from last checkpoint), streaming replication to read replicas, and Point-in-Time Recovery (PITR) to any timestamp","WAL allows concurrent writers to bypass MVCC row-version locking entirely","WAL eliminates the need for VACUUM operations on high-write tables"],"correct":1,"explanation":"The Database spec configures `archive_mode = on` and `archive_timeout = 60s` for WAL archiving and PITR via pgBackRest. Sequential disk writes avoid seek time — a spinning disk doing sequential I/O achieves ~200MB/s vs ~1MB/s random. WAL provides: crash recovery (replay from last checkpoint), streaming replication (replicas consume WAL stream), and PITR. The spec also shows `log_min_duration_statement = 200ms` for slow query detection.","hint":"Consider both the I/O performance advantage of sequential writes and the operational capabilities (recovery, replication) that WAL enables."},{"id":"q2","category":"Theory","question":"The Database architecture shows a Primary with two Read Replicas for query offloading. Which scenario MUST always route to the Primary, never a Replica?","options":["Complex SELECT queries with multiple JOINs across tables with millions of rows","SELECT COUNT(*) aggregations running analytics reports","Any write (INSERT/UPDATE/DELETE) AND reads requiring read-your-own-writes consistency — because replication lag means a replica may not yet reflect a write the Primary just committed","Full-text search queries using GIN indexes"],"correct":2,"explanation":"The spec documents read replicas for \'offloading reads\' with the replication lag caveat. Streaming replication is asynchronous — replicas may lag by milliseconds to seconds. A \'create user, then show profile\' flow fails if the profile read goes to a replica before the WAL is applied. The spec\'s pattern: route all writes and read-your-writes reads to Primary; use replicas only for analytics or explicitly lag-tolerant reads like reporting dashboards.","hint":"Streaming replication is asynchronous — a replica might be milliseconds behind. What breaks if you immediately read from a replica after writing to the primary?"},{"id":"q3","category":"Practical","question":"EXPLAIN ANALYZE reports a Sequential Scan removing 1,999,847 rows by filter for this 500 req/s production query. What index solves this most efficiently?","code":"-- EXPLAIN ANALYZE output (current):\\n-- Seq Scan on orders  (cost=0.00..98432.00)\\n-- Filter: ((customer_id = 42) AND (status = \'pending\'))\\n-- Rows Removed by Filter: 1999847\\n\\nSELECT id, total, created_at\\nFROM orders\\nWHERE customer_id = 42\\n  AND status = \'pending\'\\nORDER BY created_at DESC\\nLIMIT 20;","codeLanguage":"sql","options":["`CREATE INDEX ON orders (created_at DESC);` — ORDER BY is the expensive step","`CREATE INDEX ON orders (status);` — filtering on status eliminates the most rows","`CREATE INDEX ON orders (customer_id, status, created_at DESC);` — covers both WHERE predicates and serves ORDER BY, enabling a single index scan with pre-sorted results and no heap fetch for the selected columns","`CREATE INDEX ON orders USING GIN (status);` — GIN indexes are fastest for equality lookups"],"correct":2,"explanation":"The spec documents composite and covering indexes. For `WHERE customer_id = X AND status = Y ORDER BY created_at DESC`, a composite index `(customer_id, status, created_at DESC)` means: (1) PostgreSQL locates matching rows via the B-tree without a seq scan, (2) rows are already sorted by created_at — no sort step, (3) if we SELECT only indexed columns, it\'s an index-only scan avoiding heap access entirely. The spec\'s checklist: \'Foreign keys indexed\' and \'frequently filtered columns indexed.\'","hint":"The ideal index must satisfy both WHERE predicates AND the ORDER BY to avoid a sort step. What composite key order achieves this?"},{"id":"q4","category":"Practical","question":"Your app routes all SELECTs to a Read Replica via PgBouncer. The Primary fails and PostgreSQL promotes the Replica (takes 10–60s). What must your application code handle?","options":["Nothing — DNS automatically updates and existing connections transfer seamlessly to the promoted primary","The application must catch connection errors and \'read-only transaction\' errors, retry with exponential backoff, and reconnect to the newly promoted primary endpoint (which now accepts writes), since all existing connections to the old endpoint become invalid","All active sessions migrate transparently to the promoted primary through PgBouncer\'s built-in failover mode","The ORM polls pg_is_in_recovery() automatically and reroutes writes with zero application code changes"],"correct":1,"explanation":"The spec documents failover taking 10–60s. During promotion: old primary stops accepting connections, the replica briefly pauses, then becomes the new primary accepting writes. Applications see: connection refused errors, \'cannot execute on read-only transaction\' errors. Resilient design requires: connection retry with exponential backoff, health-check-based reconnection to the new primary endpoint (via Route53 failover or RDS endpoint change), and PgBouncer pool restart to flush stale connections.","hint":"During 10–60 seconds of failover, connections break and endpoint addresses change. What does your application need to do when it can\'t reach the database?"},{"id":"q5","category":"Theory","question":"The Database Production Checklist states: \'Money stored as DECIMAL or integer cents — never FLOAT.\' Why is FLOAT prohibited for financial data?","options":["FLOAT uses 8 bytes vs 4 bytes for INTEGER, increasing storage costs at scale","IEEE 754 binary floating-point cannot exactly represent most decimal fractions — 0.1 + 0.2 = 0.30000000000000004 — and these representation errors accumulate across millions of financial calculations, silently miscounting cents","FLOAT columns cannot be used in SUM() aggregations in PostgreSQL","FLOAT is deprecated in PostgreSQL 16 in favor of the NUMERIC type"],"correct":1,"explanation":"The spec lists \'Using FLOAT for money\' as a Common Mistake. IEEE 754 binary floats represent decimal fractions as repeating binary fractions — 0.1 in binary is 0.0001100110011… (repeating). Stored as FLOAT64, 0.1 becomes 0.10000000000000000555. Multiplied across 10 million transactions, these errors compound into real financial discrepancies. Fix: use `DECIMAL(19, 4)` for exact decimal arithmetic, or store amounts as integer cents in BIGINT (never lose the decimal by using integer math).","hint":"Open your browser console and type `0.1 + 0.2`. That IEEE 754 representation error exists in SQL FLOAT too — what does this mean for financial totals?"}]')}}]);